  "output": "## Performance Analysis — jobsquare\n\nThis is a pure Python job-scraping pipeline (fetchers → filter → dedup → notify), no frontend/React exists in this repo, so I mapped your categories to their Python equivalents: N+1 queries (SQLite), redundant computation (the \"re-render\" analogue), caching, and memory bloat.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nFor every job in the run (could be thousands across Microsoft/Amazon/Netflix boards), this does **one `SELECT` + one `INSERT`/`UPDATE` per row**, all in a Python loop:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job)\n        self._insert(cur, job, now)          # separate INSERT per row\n    else:\n        ...                                   # separate UPDATE per row\n```\n\nThat's up to 2-3× N round trips through sqlite3's Python-level statement overhead. Fix: batch-fetch existing hashes with one `IN (...)` query (chunked for SQLite's ~999 variable limit), diff in memory, then `executemany` for inserts/updates:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing = {}\n    for i in range(0, len(jobs), 900):\n        chunk = jobs[i:i + 900]\n        placeholders = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(chunk))\n        rows = self.conn.execute(\n            f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({placeholders})\",\n            [j.key for j in chunk]).fetchall()\n        existing.update({r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in rows})\n\n    new, changed, touched = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev = existing.get(job.key)\n        if prev is None:\n            new.append(job)\n        elif prev != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n        else:\n            touched.append(job.key)\n\n    rows = [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in new]\n    self.conn.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key, ..., :now, :now)\"\"\", rows)\n    rows = [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in changed]\n    self.conn.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\"\"\", rows)\n    self.conn.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\",\n                           [(now, k) for k in touched])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\n### 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:15-27` (`match`)\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job, and `match()` recompiles the include/exclude regex list **from scratch on every call**:\n\n```python\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):   # recompiled every job!\n```\n\nWith 1,000 jobs and 5 keywords, that's 5,000 needless `re.compile` calls. Compile once outside the loop:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = ...\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include_re, exclude=exclude_re,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] = (), exclude: list[re.Pattern] = (), ...):\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n\n### 3. Redundant computation — `models.py:66-69` + `store.py:76-97` (`content_hash`)\n\n`Job.content_hash` is a plain `@property` that runs a SHA-256 hash over a joined string on every access. `Store.diff` accesses it once directly (`job.content_hash`) and again indirectly via `job.to_row()` inside `_insert`/`_update` — **hashed twice per new/changed job**. Since `Job` uses `slots=True`, `functools.cached_property` won't work as-is (needs a cache slot), so either add one or just compute it once and pass it through:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass Job:\n    ...\n    _content_hash: str | None = field(default=None, repr=False, compare=False)\n\n    @property\n    def content_hash(self) -> str:\n        if self._content_hash is None:\n            blob = \"|\".join((self.title, self.location, self.url, self.department))\n            self._content_hash = hashlib.sha256(blob.encode()).hexdigest()[:16]\n        return self._content_hash\n```\n\nLow-impact at current scale, but free once the N+1 fix above is in place (it computes `to_row()` per-job anyway).\n\n### 4. Sequential I/O in notification dispatch — `notify.py:105-109`\n\n`dispatch()` runs 5 notifiers **sequentially and synchronously**, each with its own 15s timeout (SMTP has no bound at all). If Slack + webhook + email + SMS are all configured, a slow/degraded one blocks the rest — worst case adds up to 45s+ of pure waiting on a script that's otherwise fully async:\n\n```python\ndef dispatch(new: list[Job], changed: list[Job]) -> None:\n    for fn in NOTIFIERS:\n        try:\n            fn(new, changed)\n        ...\n```\n\nThese are independent, side-effecting calls to different services — a natural fit for a thread pool:\n\n```python\nfrom concurrent.futures import ThreadPoolExecutor, as_completed\n\ndef dispatch(new: list[Job], changed: list[Job]) -> None:\n    with ThreadPoolExecutor(max_workers=len(NOTIFIERS)) as ex:\n        futs = {ex.submit(fn, new, changed): fn for fn in NOTIFIERS}\n        for fut in as_completed(futs):\n            fn = futs[fut]\n            try:\n                fut.result()\n            except Exception as e:\n                print(f\"  ! notifier {fn.__name__} failed: {e}\")\n```\n\n### 5. Memory bloat — `fetchers.py` `raw` field kept on every `Job`\n\nEvery parser (`parse_greenhouse`, `parse_lever`, etc.) stores the **full raw JSON payload** on `Job.raw`. I checked — `raw` is never read anywhere outside `fetchers.py`/`models.py` (it's stripped in `to_row()` before persisting, and nothing else touches it). For big boards (Microsoft/Amazon run up to 40 pages), that's the entire fetched JSON for thousands of listings held in memory simultaneously for no downstream benefit. Since fetches for all sources run concurrently (`fetch_all`, default concurrency=8), peak working set is the sum of every source's raw payloads at once. Cheapest fix: drop the field entirely, or make it `raw: dict = field(default_factory=dict, repr=False, compare=False)` and simply stop populating it in the bulk parsers (keep it only where something downstream might need it later).\n\n### Not applicable here\n- **N+1 in the fetch layer**: pagination loops (`fetch_twosigma`, `fetch_amazon`, etc.) *look* like sequential N+1 HTTP calls, but each page's request depends on knowing whether the previous page was non-empty — that's inherent to cursor-style pagination, not a fix-able anti-pattern.\n- **React re-renders**: no frontend code exists in this repo.\n\n---\n\nWant me to apply any of these fixes? The `store.diff` batching (#1) is the highest-value one since it scales with total job count across every source.\n",
